<TEXT>
cardinal miguel obando y bravo said 
thursday he was unable to set up conciliation talks between 
nicaragua and the united states as requested by president daniel 
ortega 
also thursday foreign minister miguel descoto accused the us 
government of spreading systematic lies to discredit nicaragua 
and its preparations for free elections in 1990 
ortega publicly asked obando y bravo the roman catholic 
archbishop of managua on monday to act as a gobetween in setting 
up the talks with the bush administration resolve its differences 
with nicaraguas leftist sandinista regime 
the cardinal said he would think about it but state department 
spokesman rudi boone on tuesday rejected the offer he said an 
improvement in relations would depend on a number of factors 
including an end to nicaraguan support for leftist guerrillas in 
el salvador 
boone in washington also said nicaragua should hold free and 
fair elections under international supervision and enter into of a 
genuine dialogue with opposition groups before the us agrees to 
sit down and talk 
referring to boones statement obando y bravo wrote ortega 
saying that for the time being it is not possible to enter into a 
process of mediation because one of the parties has officially 
set conditions for the dialogue 
ortega read the obando y bravos letter at a news conference 
expressed thanks to the cardinal and said he will insist through 
other venues with the us government and president bush to accept a 
dialogue with nicaragua 
the united states cut off all aid to nicaragua in 1980 started 
supporting contra rebels the next year and slapped an economic 
embargo on this nation in 1985 to pressure the sandinistas to hold 
free and fair elections and sever military ties with soviet bloc 
nations 
us administrations have argued that soviet and cuban military 
aid to the sandinistas and nicaraguas help to the salvadoran 
guerrillas is threatening security in central america the 
sandinistas claim they have been providing only moral support to the 
salvadoran rebels 
an attempt by the united states and nicaragua to hold talks in 
mexico in 1984 ended in deadlock with the reagan administration 
accusing the sandinistas of failing to negotiate in good faith 
the 14party national opposition union on thursday asked obando y 
bravo to try and set up talks with the sandinista government to try 
and resolve these differences but the cardinal himself a sharp 
critic of the sandinistas did not respond immediately 
earlier thursday foreign minister miguel descoto accused the 
bush administration of spreading systematic lies to discredit 
nicaragua and denied allegations by vice president dan quayle that 
nicaragua is allying itself with cuba and panama to form a three way 
antius alliance 
speaking in caracas venezuela where he was attending a third 
world meeting descoto said i would take anything a us 
government official says with a ton of salt systematic lying is an 
instrument of their foreign policy the only thing he quayle needs 
for his opinions is his mouth 
descoto also denied recent allegations by bush about nicaraguas 
election procedures and said the sandinistas were strictly 
complying with the agenda for the elections in february 1990 
critics have said the government stacked a national election 
board which will supervise the balloting process in favor of the 
sandinistas also as of june 1 us citizens were required for the 
first time to get visas to enter nicaragua making it difficult for 
american observers to be there 
