<TEXT>
convicted felon and fourtime presidential 
candidate lyndon larouche announced plans thursday to run for 
congress next year 
larouche 65 a loudoun county resident wants to represent 
virginias 10th district which includes arlington half of fairfax 
and loudoun counties after filing his intent to run for congress 
with the federal election commission on june 8 larouche became the 
first democrat to announce plans to go after incumbent republican 
representative frank wolfs seat 
larouche was convicted in january in us district court in 
alexandria on charges of mail fraud conspiracy to commit mail fraud 
and conspiracy to defraud the internal revenue service he was 
sentenced to 15 years and is appealing the conviction 
he ran for president as an independent in 1976 and as a democrat 
in 1980 1984 and 1988 
asked whether he could serve his constituents well from jail 
larouche said i think this is a very turbulent period of history 
i could pop out of prison just as quick as i popped in larouche 
has maintained since his conviction that his trial was political 
larouche and his associates were convicted for a scheme in which 
they used a fundraising operation to solicit loans from people 
that they didnt pay back they failed to report the transactions to 
the government 
as a convicted felon larouche wont be eligible to vote for 
himself but he does meet constitutional requirements to run for the 
house of representatives said susan fitzhugh virginia state board 
of elections secretary 
larouche is over 25 has been a united states citizen for more 
than seven years and is an inhabitant of virginia he and five 
associates are at the alexandria jail awaiting assignments to 
federal prisons 
