<TEXT>
a policy reversal by gov michael s dukakis has 
led state and federal officials to agree on a plan to deport about 
1000 illegal aliens held in massachusetts prisons 
in 1985 dukakis issued an executive order forbidding state 
investigators from working on deportation cases unless ordered to do 
so by a court 
that order was portrayed as gesture of good will toward illegals 
at a time when the reagan administration was cracking down 
under the new policy agreed to tuesday the state will work with 
us immigration and naturalization service officials to identify 
and deport inmates of the crowded state and county prison system who 
are in the united states illegally 
when possible the state will work aggressively to get these 
people out on the next plane said human services secretary philip 
johnston who oversees massachusetts correction system 
regional ins director charles cobb who met tuesday with johnston 
to work out the plans details and has criticized dukakis order 
called the agreement a step in the right direction 
about 1300 or 10 percent of the approximately 13000 inmates 
in state prisons are illegal aliens according to johnston of the 
1300 about 1000 are eligible for immediate deportation 
most of the inmates involved have been involved in drug dealing 
and come from jamaica the dominican republic and colombia 
according to johnston 
some convicted of particularly violent crimes including four men 
serving sentences for the rape at big dans tavern in new bedford in 
1984 will remain in prison johnston said 
