china executed three men wednesday and up to 17 
others were condemned to die for their roles in studentled protests 
that challenged the power of the communist party 
the executions in shanghai were carried out despite appeals for 
clemency by president bush and other western leaders 
premier li peng denounced the foreign criticism 
he told visiting foreign secretary humayun khan of pakistan that 
most of the millions of chinese who took part nationwide in marches 
sitins and hunger strikes for a freer society would be treated 
leniently even if they had extremist opinions 
but li said the tiny minority of criminals will be punished 
according to the law 
the meeting was the first toplevel contact with a foreign 
delegation since the crackdown began june 34 when the army fired 
on students and supporters in beijing to end their prodemocracy 
demonstrations 
more than 1600 arrests have been reported nationwide since and 
the nations highest court has urged lower courts to deal swiftly 
and severely with protestrelated cases 
so far 28 people have been condemned to death the three who 
were executed the 17 who were sentenced on wednesday and eight 
others who were previously sentenced to death 
the shanghai men were convicted of setting a train on fire on 
june 6 after it plowed into a barricade set up by protesters 
killing six people 
