<TEXT>
a us supreme court ruling allowing 
newspapers to identify rape victims in some instances is unlikely to 
change voluntary policies against doing so a newspaper executive 
said 
the court ruled 63 that the florida star a jacksonville weekly 
newspaper doesnt have to pay 97500 to a rape victim whose name 
was published in 1983 wednesdays ruling limits states power to 
punish the reporting of truthful information that is lawfully 
obtained 
many news organizations including the florida star voluntarily 
withhold names of victims of sex crimes the newspapers lawyers 
said the womans name was published inadvertently 
pete weitzel managing editor of the miami herald said he didnt 
think the decision will change what newspapers do he pointed out 
that the american press has become more sensitive to privacy issues 
in recent years 
i think all this really does is say youve got to make the 
judgment yourselves said weitzel chairman of the florida society 
of newspaper editors freedom of information committee 
the committee filed a court brief on the side of the star 
it was a pretty straightforward win weitzel said it 
bascially says yes you can go after a newspaper based on privacy 
but it must be on very narrow grounds 
the justices ruled that a state can punish the publication of 
lawfully obtained information only when narrowly tailored to a 
state interest of the highest order 
that interest was not present in the stars case the court found 
allowing censorship for an interest of the highest order will 
have little practical application because that terminology 
previously has been used only for national security matters said 
attorney george rahdert who represented the star 
it raises the fundamental question of whether a privacy issue 
could ever be an interest of the highest order rahdert said 
he said the ruling could have a wide ranging effect against 
attempts at censorship 
the victims lawsuit was based on a florida law that outlaws 
printing publishing or broadcasting the names of sex crime victims 
weitzel said the editors group has long questioned the 
constitutionality of the law 
mitch franks assistant deputy state attorney general said he 
was uncertain what impact the courts decision would have on the law 
we would urge in the interest of protecting the victims of 
crime that the news media continue to adhere to their policy of not 
publishing the names of rape victims franks said 
star publisher eric o simpson said he was pleased with the 
ruling but regretted the award wasnt reversed by state courts 
we were being denied the right to publish the truth 
simpson said it constituted prior restraint 
the rape victims name had been obtained from a report posted 
apparently by mistake in the press room of the duval county 
sheriffs department 
had the court allowed the award to stand it could have lead to 
passage of laws to prevent the publication of victims names in 
other types of crimes simpson said 
a person being raped is no worse than a person being killed 
he said 
