<TEXT>
with a new test doctors may be able to begin 
treating aidsinfected babies soon after birth rather than waiting 
more than a year to make sure they truly carry the virus doctors 
reported today 
babies of infected women have about a one in three chance of 
picking up the aids virus from their mothers but until about age 16 
months there is no foolproof way of sorting out which infants are 
infected and which are not 
therefore doctors have been unable to try early treatment with 
the aids medicine azt the drug has been shown to help though not 
cure youngsters with more advanced disease 
doctors caution however that the test may miss some infected 
babies and it is still too difficult to be used routinely the 
technique known as polymerase chain reaction or pcr can spot the 
genes of viruses that have invaded blood cells 
its something of a breakthrough we have been very hindered by 
the fact that we dont have diagnostic tests in infants said dr 
martha f rogers of the us centers for disease control in atlanta 
we need that critically she added because people would 
like to start treatment with azt very early on but you are stuck 
with treating every child born to a virus positive mother with a 
fairly toxic drug and youll be treating some kids who dont have 
the infection and dont need it 
ordinarily doctors check for aids infections by testing the 
blood for antibodies to the virus those who carry antibodies are 
presumed to be infected 
this method is worthless for newborns babies whose mothers were 
infected will carry their mothers aids antibodies for months even 
if the babies themselves are not infected 
this will be the key role of pcr commented dr cody meissner 
of new england medical center in boston we will be able to do a 
test on the babys blood in the first weeks of life and hopefully 
this will differentiate between kids who are truly infected and 
those who are simply born to women who are infected 
doctors have been reluctant to treat all newborns of infected 
mothers with azt until they can find out which ones are truly 
infected otherwise they would be giving the toxic drug to twice as 
many uninfected babies as infected ones 
rogers and colleagues at six new york hospitals tried out the 
test on newborns of women infected with the aids virus they report 
their results in the new england journal of medicine 
in the study the test revealed aids infections in five of seven 
newborns who later went on to develop aids it also showed infection 
in one of eight newborns who later had nonspecific symptoms such 
as swollen lymph glands that could have been caused by the aids 
virus the test results were negative in nine infants who remained 
well 
while childhood aids infections are rare in the united states 
they are becoming a major health hazard in parts of africa another 
study in the journal describes the results of a study on 475 infants 
who were born to infected mothers at two hospitals in zaire the 
research directed by dr robert w ryder of the department of 
public health in kinshasa concludes that aids may already have 
increased infant mortality there by 15 percent 
the study found that women with more advanced aids infections are 
more likely to pass the virus to their babies during pregnancy 
infected women are also more apt to deliver babies who are premature 
or unusually small 
</TEXT>
