<TEXT>
a drug used to treat epilepsy during pregnancy to 
prevent birth defects may itself harm the unborn baby scientists 
reported today 
in the report doctors linked the drug tegretol or 
carbamazepine with minor facial abnormalities and retardation 
several other drugs to treat epilepsy which afflicts an estimated 
49 million americans also have been shown to be bad for the fetus 
physicians who treat women with seizures are in a very 
difficult position said dr ronald v lacro whose study appears 
in the new england journal of medicine 
this is the drug of choice because it seemed to be safe we 
cant say that anymore 
cibageigy which makes tegretol said the study is a reminder 
that the risks and benefits of anticonvulsant drugs need to be 
weighed carefully but the medicine should still be considered for 
epileptics who want to have children 
we feel that our past data show that tegretol is a good option 
for epileptic women we still feel that way said spokeswoman 
cathy kernen 
lacro a pediatrician at childrens hospital in boston was a 
coauthor of the study directed by dr kenneth lyons jones of the 
university of californiasan diego 
the report found evidence that women who took tegretol during 
pregnancy were more likely to produce babies with delayed 
development and mental retardation they also were more likely to 
have unusual facial formations including upward slanting eyes 
long upper lips and short noses and incomplete development of 
finger nails 
studies have shown that severe epileptic seizures during 
pregnancy can temporarily interrupt the flow of blood to the fetus 
causing brain damage however epileptic women have an increased 
risk of producing babies with minor birth defects even if they 
dont have seizures during their pregnancies 
counseling has to start before pregnancy for these women 
said lacro if the woman has severe enough seizures and needs the 
medicine then by all means you have to give it but there is no 
completely safe therapy other than being off medications 
the researchers first identified the pattern of birth defects in 
eight children who had been exposed to the drug before birth they 
confirmed it by evaluating 48 other children whose mothers had taken 
the medicine 
they found that 11 percent of those exposed had facial 
abnormalities 26 percent had incomplete finger nails and 20 percent 
were slow to develop 
only one youngster with delayed development was old enough to 
take an intelligence test that child a 6 year old had an iq of 65 
cibageigy criticized the study for serious methodological 
problems it noted that the doctors used women who did not have 
epilepsy in a comparison group the higher risk of birth defects 
among the children of the epileptic women might have resulted from 
the epilepsy not the medications 
lacro said i think that what we are seeing is due to the drug 
if the changes that we saw were due to seizures alone then we would 
see the same pattern of malformations for all kinds of seizure 
drugs i think the defects are drug specific but i cant prove 
that 
</TEXT>
