classaction suit claiming the liedetector tests violated both a 
california labor code ban on involuntary polygraphs and the state 
constitutional right to privacy 
the agreement announced wednesday is subject to approval by a 
superior court judge 
it tells all employers that workers do not hang up their rights 
at the door of the workplace brad seligman a lawyer for the 
plaintiffs said in a statement 
the suit was filed on behalf of all applicants and employees of 
the federated group in california since nov 23 1983 
the company may have given 15000 polygraph tests since 1983 the 
plaintiffs said 
gregory pratt chief financial officer for atari corp said the 
tests were discontinued shortly after atari bought the federated 
group in 1987 for 67 million 
according to the suit one woman was told she had the job 
before she was given a polygraph test in which she was asked if she 
had ever been to a psychiatrist or a therapist 
she refused to answer saying the question was too personal and 
was told she was neurotic and high strung according to the 
suit she did not get the job 
