<TEXT>
home ownership among young americans is 
declining alarmingly and threatens to produce a permanent 
underclass of disadvantaged renters a harvard university study 
released today said 
the annual report on the state of the nations housing released 
by harvards joint center for housing studies said the 
homeownership rate for households in the 2529 age group fell to 
362 percent in 1988 in 1980 it was 433 percent 
for households in the 3034 age group the rate fell to 526 
percent off nearly 10 percentage points from the 1976 rate of 624 
the report also said that 30 percent of the nearly 57 million 
unsbsidized housing units renting for less than 300 a month are 
physically inadequate and at risk of loss 
it said singleparent households accounting for an increasing 
share of the nations total population of children are the most 
vulnerable to the cost crunch 
the median income of a single parent under 25 was 6223 in 1988 
down 15 percent in inflationadjusted terms from 1974 the report 
said 
at the same time it said 71 percent of all singleparent 
households pay more than 50 percent of their incomes for rent 
because it is rooted in fundamental social economic and 
demographic factors this trend is not easily reversed the study 
said left unchecked it threatens to produce a permanent 
underlcass of disadvantaged renters and to jeopardize the longterm 
financial security of future generations 
the study offered no specific solutions to the housing problems 
it identified saying that they are subject to debate but that 
policymakers must act to develop creative approaches to advance 
the goal of decent housing for all 
the study was coauthored by william apgar and denise dipasquale 
professors at the joint center 
 
</TEXT>
