the supreme court today made it easier for 
communities to turn down the volume on rock concerts upholding new 
york citys effort to avoid earsplitting noise levels in central 
park 
the justices by a 63 vote said officials may require sponsors 
of rock concerts in the parks naumberg acoustic bandshell to use a 
sound system operated by a citydesignated engineer 
that requirement does not violate the freedomofexpression 
guarantees of the constitutions first amendment justice anthony m 
kennedy wrote for the court 
the decision reversed a federal appeals court ruling that said 
city officials had to devise a less restrictive way to satisfy 
their concern over noise levels 
this lessrestrictivealternative analysis has never been a 
part of the inquiry into the validity of a time place and manner 
regulation on expression kennedy said 
he added the citys sound amplification guideline is narrowly 
tailored to serve the substantial and contentneutral governmental 
interests of avoiding excessive sound volume and providing 
sufficient amplification within the bandshell concertground 
accordingly it is valid under the first amendment as a 
reasonable regulation of the place and manner of expression 
kennedy said 
in a dissenting opinion justice thurgood marshall said the court 
plays to our shared impatience with loud noise to obscure the 
damage that it does to our first amendment rights 
calling new yorks requirement for a cityrun sound system at 
rock concerts an impermissible prior restraint marshall said 
because judgments that sounds are too loud noiselike or 
discordant can mask disapproval of the music itself government 
control of the soundmixing equipment necessitates detailed and 
neutral standards 
quoting one music critic the 80yearold marshall added new 
music always sounds loud to old ears 
he was joined in dissent by justices william j brennan and john 
paul stevens 
