<TEXT>
the supreme court on thursday made it easier 
for communities to turn down the volume at rock concerts a decision 
freespeech advocates found disquieting 
the court by a 63 vote upheld new york citys effort to avoid 
earsplitting noise levels in central park by requiring sponsors of 
rock concerts to use a sound system operated by a citydesignated 
engineer 
such requirements dont violate the freedomofexpression 
guarantees of the constitutions first amendment the court said 
but dana beal political coordinator for a concertsponsoring 
organization called rock against racism said the ruling strikes at 
the heart of rock 
bit by bit each municipality in the country will be able to 
turn rock n roll into easy listening music beal said 
the decision reversed a federal appeals court ruling that would 
have forced city officials to devise a less restrictive way to deal 
with what they deem excessively loud entertainment 
this lessrestrictivealternative analysis has never been a 
part of the inquiry into the validity of a time place and manner 
regulation on expression justice anthony m kennedy wrote for the 
court 
the citys sound amplification guideline is narrowly tailored 
to serve substantial and contentneutral governmental 
interests he wrote accordingly it is valid under the first 
amendment as a reasonable regulation of the place and manner of 
expression 
in a dissenting opinion justice thurgood marshall said the court 
plays to our shared impatience with loud noise to obscure the 
damage that it does to our first amendment rights 
marshall called new yorks requirement for a cityrun sound 
system an impermissible prior restraint and said such 
government actions should be subjected to the same scrutiny as 
regulations based on an expressions content 
judgments that sounds are too loud noiselike or discordant 
can mask disapproval of the music itself he said 
quoting one music critic the 80yearold marshall said new 
music always sounds loud to old ears 
he was joined in dissent by justices william j brennan and john 
paul stevens 
the citys noisecontrol campaign is aimed at protecting visitors 
to central parks sheep meadow a 13acre area decreed a quiet 
zone by mayor ed koch in 1985 and residents of fashionable 
central park west 
the city policy was challenged by rock against racism which 
sponsors an annual program of speakers and musical groups in the 
parks naumberg acoustic bandshell 
the losing lawyer in the case was william kunstler who a day 
earlier found himself on the winning side when the justices ruled 
that burning the american flag is a form of constitutionally 
protected political protest 
what the court gives with one hand it takes away with the 
other kunstler said now art is subject to government control 
something the framers of the constitution certainly would not have 
countenanced 
</TEXT>
