<TEXT>
natural erosion apparently has blunted 
a spike of light dubbed the sun dagger that ancient pueblo 
indians are believed to have used to mark the summer solstice 
the dagger was formed by light shining between 9foottall 
sandstone slabs sitting just below the top of the 500foottall 
fajada butte in chaco canyon in northwestern new mexico on the 
solstice the longest day of the year the light would shine on a 
spiralshaped petroglyph etched on rock behind the slabs 
but erosion apparently caused a rock to shift and on wednesday 
the daggershaped pattern of light missed its summersolstice mark 
on the petroglyph for perhaps the first time in 1000 years 
researchers said instead the light shined above and to the left of 
the indian pattern 
were used to this thing acting like a clock physicist rolf 
sinclair said wednesday 
the dagger widened and lengthened into an overgrown carrot 
said anna sofaer an artist and archaeoastronomer who discovered 
the dagger in 1977 in chaco culture national historical park which 
contains numerous ancient stone dwellings 
the rock formation also cast distinctive light patterns at the 
winter solstice and the fall and spring equinoxes when day and 
night are of equal length 
the petroglyph near the canyons south entrance was believed to 
have been carved between ad 950 and 1150 at the peak of the 
anasazi culture that once thrived in chaco canyon 
sinclair sofaer and others contend rocks originally might have 
been manipulated to cause the sunlight patterns 
but on sunday a group that included sinclair discovered that one 
of the rock slabs had shifted and had altered the phenomenon 
its very serious and sad ms sofaer said we knew when we 
first saw the site that it had a fragility that was remarkable 
michael zelik a physics and astronomy professor at the 
university of new mexico said the alteration raises questions about 
how much or how often rocks have moved previously at the site and 
about just how old it really is 
however sinclair said its clear the rocks have not moved much 
if at all over the years he said the erosion which caused the rock 
to slip might be due to 10 years of relatively wet weather at chaco 
</TEXT>
