<TEXT>
a chronology compiled by the national 
geographic society of the fate of the german world war ii battleship 
bismarck 
1936 construction starts in hamburg of the 820foot ship with a 
displacement when fully loated of more than 50000 tons carrying 
eight 15inch guns 12 59inch guns and 16 41inch guns and a crew 
of 2200 and capable of a top speed of 30 knots 
feb 14 1939 on st valentines day adolf hitler launches the 
ship 
may 19 1941 after more than two years in fitting and shakedown 
cruises the bismarck sets sail from gdynia poland with orders to 
sink allied merchant ships in the atlantic while evading engagement 
with allied warships 
may 20 1941 a swedish cruiser spots the bismarck and its 
escort the prinz eugen off the coast of neutral sweden later they 
are sighted off the coast of norway 
may 21 1941 british spitfires over the bergenkorsfjord region 
of norway spot the two german ships the british send the battle 
cruiser hood to join other british ships on patrol in the denmark 
strait 
may 22 1941 more british forces head for the search zone 
may 23 1941 in the denmark strait beteen greenland and 
iceland the british cruisers suffolk and norfolk sight the german 
ship threading through a minefield the bismarck opens fire but the 
british retire safely the british follow the germans despite rain 
and snow storms and dangerous ice floes the hood and the prince of 
wales are closing in from about 250 miles away 
may 24 at 535 am the hood and prince of wales sight the 
bismarck and open fire the germans return fire at 601 am a 
massive explosion sinks the hood leaving only three of its 1419 
crewmen alive the bismarck suffers a ruptured fuel tank the 
bismarck engages the british again in the evening the prinz eugen 
escapes the bismarcks commander decides to make for a french port 
for repairs a british force heads to the area from gibraltar 
around midnight nine british biplanes attack causing little damage 
may 25 about 3 am the bismarck evades its chasers and heads 
for the safety of uboat patrols and luftwaffe air cover near the 
coast of france 
may 26 a british plane spots the bismarck in a lastditch 
effort to stop it before it reaches safety planes from a british 
carrier score two torpedo hits that wreck the bismarcks steering 
gear and jam her rudders only hours from safety the bismarcks 
fate is sealed 
may 27 at 847 am a british force opens up on the limping 
bismarck putting its main guns out of action by 10 am the 
bismarck is a battered hulk by 1039 am it has capsized and sunk 
coming to rest upright on the ocean floor with only 115 of its crew 
of 2200 rescued 
</TEXT>
