the soviet union on thursday strengthened its ties 
with iran agreeing to exchange delegations of moslem religious 
leaders and indicating it would send weaponry to its islamic 
neighbor 
the agreement with iran came as the soviet union struggles with a 
resurgence of islamic fundamentalism and conflicts between its 
christians and 50 million moslems 
the agreement was part of a broad declaration signed by president 
mikhail s gorbachev and iranian parliament speaker hashemi 
rafsanjani whose visit to the soviet union has defrosted a decade 
of icy relations 
it implies future soviet weapons sales to iran by promising the 
superpowers cooperation in strengthening the defense capacity 
of its southern neighbor at the same time the document commits 
both nations to strive to rid the world of aggression 
rafsanjani later sidestepped questions about arms deals he said 
only that iran was trying to be selfsufficient in arms but has some 
technical requirements that we would like to see met by various 
sources 
in washington secretary of state james a baker iii told the 
house foreign affairs committee that us policy toward iran would 
be guided by developments in the country and not by its 
relationship with the soviet union 
the soviet union was iraqs major weapons supplier during the 
eightyear iraniraq war but even then the soviets arranged for 
the sale of arms to iran through third countries 
during a state dinner wednesday rafsanjani invited gorbachev to 
visit iran if gorbachev accepts he would be the first leader of a 
major power to visit tehran since the islamic revolution in 1979 
