britain has signed an agreement with the united 
states to help develop a new airlaunched nuclear missile a defense 
ministry spokesman said thursday 
the spokesman who refused to be identified said the agreement 
for a us feasibility study on updating one of britains key 
strategic weapons a sensitive issue with the soviet union was 
signed dec 1 but not announced at the time 
officials acknowledged the agreement after janes defense weekly 
reported it it said the american company martin marietta corp is 
investigating with british aerospace plc the possibility of 
developing a new tactical airtosurface missile 
the missile with a range of 250370 miles and fired from tornado 
bombers would replace britains aging we177 freefall nuclear bomb 
the spokesman said the us agreement did not mean that the 
british were abandoning a possible deal with france 
we have not signed a similar memorandum of understanding with 
the french but both american and french systems remain open as 
options for consideration he said 
however the anglofrench project appeared virtually certain of 
being abandoned it involved developing a longerrange version of 
frances asmp nuclear airtosurface missiles 
negotiations began about two years ago there has been no sign of 
progress and defense ministry sources have said in recent months 
that the french system is unsuitable for british bombers 
the strategic importance of airlaunched nuclear weapons has 
increased following the 1987 agreement between the united states and 
the soviet union to withdraw all their mediumrange landbased 
nuclear weapons from europe 
the soviet union has complained that updating airlaunched 
missiles violates the spirit of the 1987 agreement 
janes an authoritative magazine said a firm decision on 
developing with us companies a new weapon for britain was expected 
in 1992 
