<TEXT>
a retired us air force colonel said 
thursday he had made a solo flight over the north pole in a 
singleengine plane 
charles mack said he flew from point barrow alaska to helsinki 
in 19 hours 58 minutes and claimed a world record for the solo 
2970mile flight in his beechcraft bonanza be36 there was no 
independent verification 
officials at helsinkis airport said mack landed about 7 pm 
but they did not know were he came from 
mack 68 of hollywood fla said he planned the trip for 
midsummer so he could use the arctics seasonal 24hour sunlight to 
help him navigate he said he had to make adjustments to his 
gyrocompass every 20 minutes to keep from straying off course 
he also navigated by sun sightings a sun dial and radio 
directionfinding equipment 
i chose helsinki from point barrow to helsinki because its a 
straight line over the north pole he said if i went to sweden 
then somebody could say i went beside the north pole 
mack said he flew over ice for most of the trip and said clouds 
often blocked his view but he made some videotapes he flew near 
the west end of spitzbergen island and over finland to helsinki in 
the beechcraft 
he had planned to fly at 160 mph at an altitude of 3000 to 5000 
feet 
mack a former fighter pilot said he has more than 14000 hours 
of flight time including solo flights from paris to new york and 
back 
he left south florida on june 13 and plans to return via paris 
iceland and new york next month 
