<TEXT>
nearly three months after it caused the 
nations worst oil spill the damaged tanker exxon valdez will be 
towed out of prince william sound on friday for a 25 million repair 
job in san diego authorities said 
the coast guard said the 987foot vessel will leave the shelter 
of outside bay on the southwest side of naked island in the heart of 
the sound during the morning weather permitting 
the exxon valdez has been undergoing temporary repairs at outside 
bay since about two weeks after it ran aground at bligh reef on 
march 24 ripping its hull and spilling nearly 11 million gallons of 
crude oil drawn from wells on alaskas north slope 
eight of the vessels 13 tanks were penetrated by the reef and 
divers reported finding rocks as large as small cars in the cargo 
hold but the tanks have been cleaned to the point that small 
schools of herring and salmon have been reported living in them the 
hull also has been steamcleaned 
divers drilled numerous holes along many cracks in the hull and 
plated over them to keep the cracks from spreading one crack was 
said to run through the hull until about midship the cracks had to 
be immobilized with plates out of concern that rough seas could 
break the vessel in half 
several of the vessels tanks remain unsealed exxon spokesman 
joe tucker said coast guard and salvage officials said air pressure 
in the tanks would keep seawater at maneageable levels 
the tanker will be towed by two tugs and accompanied by a 
salvage vessel and a third tug but tucker said the tankers engines 
are in working order and will be be used at the skippers discretion 
since the spill oil has soiled more than 700 miles of alaskas 
southern coastline some of the oil has flushed out of the sound and 
traveled with gulf of alaska currents some 400 miles to kodiak 
island and the alaska peninsula 
workers have recovered more than 26000 birds killed by the oil 
although biologists say the figure probably represents 10 percent or 
less of the overall toll other casualties have included more than 
50 eagles and nearly 800 sea otters 
the spill forced closure of numerous herring and salmon fisheries 
and severely curtailed others 
exxon has more than 9000 people backed up by 800 boats and a 
small air force working to clean up the spill exxon said this week 
it already has spent more than 200 million on the job and the 
state has billed exxon more than 12 million for oilspill expenses 
under a procedure established two weeks after the spill the 
state sends its bills to exxon which pays most of the suppliers and 
contractors directly and reimburses the state for outofpocket 
costs said michael nizich administrative services director for 
gov steve cowpers office 
batches of invoices have been sent almost daily to exxon some 
of them were pretty hefty in size nizich said 
a coast guard officer will be on board the exxon valdez until it 
leaves prince william sound about 60 miles from naked island and 
again when the vessel nears san diego where the ship was built 
tucker said seven exxon officers and four salvage experts would 
be on board throughout the voyage expected to take about 20 days 
at about 6 mph 
one worker was killed during the cleanup and there have numerous 
injuries in boat and plane accidents as well as from falls on 
oilslickened beaches 
the former captain of the exxon valdez joseph hazelwood has 
been charged with six criminal counts arising from the spill among 
other things the state alleges he was drunk at the time 
hazelwood has pleaded innocent to all charges court officials 
say it is unlikely his trial will take place until fall or early 
winter 
