<TEXT>
the nations chemical manufacturers said 
thursday they have abandoned their previous opposition and now 
support new legislation to control airborne toxic chemicals 
we intend to be a constructive player in the legislative 
process robert c forney a du pont co executive told the house 
energy and commerce environment subcommittee on behalf of the 
chemical manufacturers association 
forney said the chemical industrys trade group previously 
believed new legislation was unnecessary but has now concluded the 
environmental protection agency cannot adequately regulate air 
emissions under the existing law 
but forney and other industry witnesses clashed with rep henry 
a waxman dcalif the subcommittee chairman over the need for 
provisions designed to prevent accidental chemical releases 
forney said a great deal has been done by industry to prevent 
accidents and we dont believe additional legislation is 
required 
i find it difficult to understand that position waxman said 
citing environmental protection agency figures showing there were 
more than 4700 accidential releases between 1980 and 1987 the 120 
most serious releases killed 145 people injured more than 5000 
and caused nearly 250000 to evacuate their homes waxman said 
gerald v poje of the national wildlife federation said it is 
essential that any legislation include provisions to deal with 
chemical accidents such as the disaster in bhopal india in 1984 in 
that case more than 3000 people died when the rupture of a storage 
tank unleased deadly methyl isocyanate 
industrial facilities and communities are unprepared to 
understand and respond to the consequences of chemical accidents 
he said testifying for the national clean air coalition 
representing environmental groups 
one house bill supported by waxman and environmental groups 
would require epa to develop a list of substances most likely to 
endanger the public through accidental releases to the air and issue 
regulations to prevent such releases 
the epa has recently disclosed that some 27 billion pounds of 
toxic substances go into the air each year but the agency only 
regulates only seven of more than 200 chemicals that are released 
according to the agency some 360 million pounds involve 
suspected carcinogens contributing to between 1500 and 3000 fatal 
cancers each year chemical emissions also are factors in 
respiratory disease and birth defects 
a number of legislative proposals including a clean air package 
unveiled this month by president bush would force industry to use 
the best available technology to reduce emissions the proposals 
would regulate either the chemicals themselves or set limits for 
industrial categories such as steel mills or pulp and paper 
industry witnesses told the subcommittee however many of the 
solutions proposed so far would be too harsh and should be changed 
improvement can be made by adopting provisions for 
reasonable technology instead of the best available said terry f 
yosie vice president for health and environment of the american 
petroleum institute the trade group for the oil industry 
the controls he said should be placed only on those sources 
found to be significant emitters of toxic air pollutants 
