<TEXT>
several witnesses who object to smoking urged 
congress on thursday to extend and expand a nosmoking policy on 
short airline flights but the tobacco industry insisted that health 
research doesnt justify a ban 
more than two dozen witnesses submitted testimony at a house 
public works and transportation aviation subcommittee hearing on 
several bills that would either make the temporary ban permanent or 
expand it to cover all flights smoking is outlawed on domestic 
flights of less than two hours but the rule is to lapse in april 
1990 unless congress acts 
witnesses ranged from a flight attendant who said her health was 
ruined serving smoking passengers to an indoor air expert who said 
there are worse health hazards including infectious disease in 
an airliner cabin than smoke 
opponents including tobacco interests and some lawmakers urged 
that congress await the results of a transportation department study 
of the air aboard airliners before enacting any new law the study 
is expected to be completed before the ban is lifted 
only a total ban on airline smoking will adequately protect the 
health and safety of airline passengers and flight crews said 
rep richard j durbin dill who is sponsoring legislation that 
would give congress a choice of making the ban permanent or 
expanding it to cover all commercial flights 
it is our job to esnure that those especially sensitive to 
cigarette smoke are free of having it foisted upon them in the 
confines of an airplane cabin said rep robert g torricelli 
dnj 
reps lindsay thomas rga and tom delay rtexas however 
echoed the tobacco industrys stand that no legislation should be 
passed before the airliner air quality study is completed 
i hope we will find a solution to this problem which will 
protect the rights of both those who choose to smoke and those who 
have decided not to do so said thomas 
representatives of several antismoking groups the american 
medical association the american association for respiratory care 
and the association of flight attendants called for a permanent ban 
of smoking on all flights saying smoking poses a proven health 
hazard to nonsmoking passengers and crew as well as to smokers 
flight attendant cathy gilbertsilva said working on flights 
where smoking was allowed severely affected her health she 
complained of worsening sinus infections bronchial problems 
laryngitis scratchy throat and blocked ears 
a total ban will not cure me but i know i will not get worse 
and i can continue in the job i have grown to love without fear for 
my health she said 
charles o whitley of the tobacco institute said a permanent ban 
would unjustly abandon any effort to accommodate smokers 
he said studies show that a nonsmoking passenger would have to 
make eight continuous new yorktotokyo roundtrip flights before 
being exposed to the nicotine equivalent of a single cigarette 
gray robinson president of a company that specializes in 
fighting indoor air pollution acva atlantic inc said an airline 
passenger is more likely to get sick from bacteria fungi and 
viruses floating in the poorly ventilated air tan from cigarette 
smoke 
he said there is no scientific data to justify a smoking ban but 
took no position on the legislation 
ironically there has been no evidence of excessive levels of 
carbon monoxide airborne particulates or nicotine all of which 
have been linked to tobacco smoke as a source robinson said 
for 60 cents per passenger ventilation can be increased to 
healthy levels on a boeing 747 robinson said 
he recommended that the committee pass legislation requiring 
improved ventilation and filtration of air on planes with regular 
inspections and monitoring of air quality levels 
