<TEXT>
the prosecution said thursday that a 
us soldier who admits giving military secrets to east germany 
handed communist officials information on how the army would respond 
to an attack 
a court martial is hearing the case of spec 4 michael a peri 
22 of laguna niguel calif who changed his plea from not guilty 
to guilty of espionage in a surprise move at wednesdays opening 
session 
peri left the 11th armored cavalry regiment in fulda late on feb 
20 taking with him two computer discs containing classified 
information and a laptop computer he was found to be missing the 
next day he returned voluntarily to his unit on march 4 
peri told the court on wednesday he went to east germany because 
he had problems at work and was frustrated with his job 
i was never really sure what i was going to do at all he was 
quoted as saying by the militarys unofficial stars and stripes 
newspaper i really didnt have a plan everything had been 
wrong i wasnt enjoying myself i wanted to start over somewhere 
else 
peri could receive a maximum sentence of life in prison on the 
expionage charge he faces lesser charges of absent without leave 
and wrongfully appropriating government property 
chief prosecutor maj michael graham on thursday sketched this 
sequence of events in connection with peris absence 
late on feb 20 peri went to the regiments intelligence office 
where he worked and removed a laptop computer and two floppy discs 
containing classified information on the units general defense 
plans 
the plans dealt with how the 11th armored cavalry a frontline 
defense unit would react in case of an attack from the soviet bloc 
the same day peri drove a military vehicle about 60 miles to a 
spot near the east german border he abandoned the vehicle when it 
got stuck in a wooded area walked to a border fence and climbed 
over it carrying computer and discs 
graham said peri wandered around in east germany for about two 
hours then went to a communist border guard tower and turned 
himself over to the east germans later handing over computer and 
discs to unidentified east german officials in east berlin 
the prosecutor said analysis later showed the computer had been 
accessed and set up to print out material meaning the east 
germans had copied the information 
graham then went into detail on exchanges between us and east 
german officials after peris abandoned vehicle was found on feb 24 
he said the east germans informed the us embassy in east berlin 
on march 3 that they had released peri to travel to a country of 
his choice and that on the same day the east germans returned 
the computer and discs to peri who traveled by train to salzburg 
austria 
he stayed in one of the most expensive hotels in salzburg on 
the night of march 3 and the next day began traveling by train for 
his home unit in fulda where he was later arrested the prosecutor 
said 
peri sat quietly during the session occasionally whispering to 
his chief defense counsel maj william d stokes 
his parents fred and winnie peri and sister desiree from 
orange county calif were also present and sat listening quietly 
the court martial proceedings are slated to continue friday with 
testimony from peris military associates and medical experts who 
have examined him 
