<TEXT>
president jose eduardo dos santos of 
marxist angola and rebel leader jonas savimbi shook hands thursday 
and agreed to end 14 years of civil war reports said 
the accord came at the end of an african summit on angola 
attended by 14 african heads of state 
it provides for a ceasefire in angola to start at midnight 
friday 7 pm friday edt according to zairian officials quoted by 
the french news agency agence francepresse 
the meeting between dos santos and savimbi was their first since 
the civil war began in 1975 savimbi heads the usbacked national 
union for the total independence of angola known as unita 
the reconciliation follows a usbrokered regional peace accord 
signed in new york in december under which south africa agreed to 
grant independence to namibia and halt aid to savimbis rebels in 
exchange for the withdrawal of 50000 cuban troops backing dos 
santos government 
angola cuba and south africa signed the accord the rebels are 
not party to the agreement 
thursdays peace announcement was called the declaration of 
gbadolite after the town in northern zaire where the summit was 
held it is the hometown of president mobutu sese soko of zaire and 
lies 700 miles northeast of kinshasa the capital 
a commission headed by mobutu is to be established to bring about 
national reconciliation in angola 
the historic handshake followed five hours of delay during which 
hard talks took place zairian officials were quoted as saying 
president moussa traore of mali head of the organization of 
african unity which held the summit was quoted as saying in a 
closing speech that a new page had been turned in african history 
this brotherly handshake between dr jonas savimbi and 
president dos santos symbolizes the end of civil war in angola 
which will open up a new era devoted to economic and social 
development 
reports said a snag developed until savimbi agreed to remain in 
his bush headquarters until elections expected to be held in two 
years 
earlier he had refused to go into exile in the united states 
we can now give angola hope for peace unity and development 
zambias president kenneth kaunda said according to the official 
portuguese news agency lusa 
in washington 19 members of congress on wednesday urged dos 
santos to negotiate wtih the rebels as the only means to end the 
tragic civil war in angola 
