<TEXT>
a plane carrying 60 people slammed into a 
mountain in the andes reportedly splitting in half and all aboard 
were killed the air force said thursday 
the aircraft an air force plane crashed near the town of tarma 
100 miles east of lima wednesday according to a communique 
earlier thursday gen edgar sullca flores police chief of 
huancayo city in the central highlands said the plane was carrying 
42 people including crew and passengers 
peasants from uyubamba village said they watched the aircraft 
break into two from the eastern mountain slopes flores said 
the communique said 42 of the victims had been identified an air 
force spokesman said no foreigners were among the passengers 
the air force did not say how many of the dead were civilians and 
how many were military personnel the communique did not indicate 
what might have caused the crash 
the aircraft a canadianmade buffalo bimotor cargo plane 
converted to passenger service left the jungle town of san ramon 
126 miles northeast of lima 
the air force provides passenger service on its planes to remote 
towns in perus eastern amazon jungle because the routes are not 
profitable for civilian airlines 
also wednesday an aeroperu jetliner made an emergency landing at 
limas international airport on a flight from cuzco 
airport officials said the landing gear on the plane a dc8 
would not come down the aircraft circled the airport for more than 
an hour consuming its remaining fuel to reduce the chances of fire 
during the emergency landing 
the aircraft finally was able to land without any of the 148 
passengers suffering injuries 
aeroperu is a governmentowned airline 
six civilian and military planes have crashed in peru in the past 
two years 
critics blame most accidents on poor maintenance because of a 
shortage of spare parts 
peru is suffering its worst recession in history weighed down by 
annual inflation of more than 5000 percent 
