making his first appearance in court during the trial pleaded 
unsuccessfully for the release of the four pending an appeal 
willie k chambers 35 of san diego and brian j brinson 31 
frederick p doolittle 28 and constance z jackson 38 all of los 
angeles were convicted of firstdegree manslaughter may 12 in the 
death of dayna broussard 
dayna endured hundreds of blows for stealing food from another 
child oct 13 according to testimony 
several children forced to witness the discipline session 
testified that dayna was slammed against a wall kicked tripped 
slapped dropped on the floor shoved bitten spit upon and hung 
out a window 
jackson who beat five other ecclesia children with an electrical 
cord was convicted june 5 of five counts each of seconddegree 
assault and firstdegree criminal mistreatment 
clackamas county circuit judge john lowe sentenced jackson to 10 
years in prison to be served after the manslaughter sentence on 
that conviction she will be eligible for parole in seven years 
defense lawyers asked that their clients receive light sentences 
since none had criminal records but prosecutor alfred j french iii 
urged the maximum penalty for all four 
chambers who got the stiffest penalty of the four will be 
eligible for parole in 10 years 
the 50 or more blows dealt by chambers were mainly to blame for 
the girls death lowe said 
chambers described dayna during the trial as a strongwilled 
strongbodied worldclass athlete lowe recalled but she was 
not yet a worldclass athlete she was an 8yearold girl 
jackson was convicted of striking and biting dayna 
it took more guts for dayna broussard to bite you in the leg 
than for a prisoner of war to spit in the face of her captors 
lowe told her 
brinson and doolittle who held the girl down will each have to 
serve 40 months before being eligible for parole 
no human being could have participated without asking hasnt 
this gone far enough lowe said of the two 
defense attorney ron thom said the sentences will be appealed 
broussard who testified under a 1987 law that allows crime 
victims or their families to speak at sentencing broke down once 
during his rambling 20minute testimony 
im walking a tightrope he explained to the court 
when i dont show any emotion im inhuman broussard said 
when i do express my feelings people think im faking i would 
like to assure you my daughters loss is serious to me 
he declined to comment after the sentencing 
broussard 35 formed ecclesia in los angeles tough watts area 
to steer ghetto children away from drugs and crime and toward 
rigorous athletic training 
he criticized the news media thursday for calling his 
organization a cult and portraying him as a madman or someone who 
doesnt have any sense 
broussard was in los angeles at the time of the beating at a 
farmhouse east of portland he has denied all along that dayna was 
beaten saying that children in the group were spanked as part of 
the groups strict disciplinary policy 
fiftythree children 6 weeks to 16 years old were taken into 
state protective custody after daynas death they are living with 
foster parents or with relatives 
