<TEXT>
british conglomerate hanson trust plc made a 48 
billion buyout offer thursday for consolidated gold fields plc 
going after the mining giant that two months ago escaped a hostile 
takeover attempt by another suitor 
gold fields quickly advised shareholders not to accept the bid 
but indicated it was willing to talk with hanson which owns 
businesses operations ranging from brewing to brickmaking in britain 
and the united states 
hanson offered 1430 pounds a share about 2229 at current 
exchange rates for gold fields one of the worlds biggest gold 
mining companies and owner of a 493 percent stake in newmont mining 
corp the biggest us gold miner 
hanson also said it had agreed to acquire the 299 percent stake 
in gold fields held by minorco sa the investment group that failed 
in a 546 billion hostile takeover attempt of the company 
gold fields shares jumped 170 pounds about 263 to 1423 
pounds a share about 2205 on the london stock exchange following 
news of the offer 
lord hanson chairman of the conglomerate called the offer a 
full and fair price 
but rudolph agnew chairman and chief executive of gold fields 
advised his stockholders not to sell yet saying the offer 
undervalued the companys assets however agnew also said he would 
meet with hanson to impress upon him the true worth of gold 
fields an indication he might seek a sweetened bid 
gold fields shares had fallen after a us court in april refused 
to lift an injunction blocking on antitrust grounds the takeover 
attempt by minorco which is controlled by south africas powerful 
oppenheimer mining family 
minorco had argued it would sell gold fields stakes in newmont 
and a number of other major mining operations if its takeover 
succeeded but the court sided with government concerns that the 
acquisition of gold fields sizable holdings could lessen competition 
in gold and strategic metals markets 
minorco had received acceptances of its offer from about 25 
percent of gold fields shareholders which combined with the 299 
percent it already owned would have given minorco control of gold 
fields 
unlike minorco hanson is a serious company and any approach 
from it has to be carefully considered said agnew however 
hansons opening offer completely fails to reflect the value of gold 
fields it would benefit hansons shareholders but it does not 
sufficiently benefit ours 
minorco chief executive michael edwardes said his company viewed 
the sale of its gold fields shares to hanson as a very 
satisfactory outcome minorco would receive 9152 million pounds 
143 billion from the sale of its 64 million shares 
hanson is involved in tobacco bricks electricals cement tools 
and other basic industries and made pretax profits last year of 
137 billion in the united states its subsidiaries include kidde 
inc the diversified manufacturer smith corona inc the 
typewriter maker durkee foods corp hygrade food products corp 
and scm chemicals inc 
gold fields besides its mining interests manufactures a range 
of products that analysts say complement many hanson business lines 
with little overlap 
robert haville an analyst at brokerage morgan stanley 
international in london said hansons bid for gold fields was a 
reasonably pitched intelligent offer 
gold fields shareholders would find hansons cash offer far more 
appealing than the cashandshare proposal minorco made 
institutions will consider it very attractive indeed said 
haville 
