<TEXT>
federal investigators are looking into a charge that 
an eastern airlines pilot with a broken foot and two newly hired 
copilots flew into a difficult south american airport a newspaper 
reported thursday 
eastern union sources said the captain ron neville suffered a 
broken foot in a car accident june 15 on his way to the airport in 
asuncion paraguay despite the injury neville continued flying 
even though a broken foot could make him unqualified for duty the 
sources told the post of west palm beach fla for an article 
published thursday 
one stop on the flight was in la paz bolivia an airport 
easterns operations manual designates as one at which only the 
captain can make takeoffs and landings the airport is in the 
mountains and nearby terrain rises 8000 feet above the airport 
flying an airliner with such an injury is dangerous because foot 
pedals help steer the plane and heavy pressure is required in some 
wind conditions or if an engine fails the union sources said 
eastern officials said the claim was an effort by its striking 
unions to hurt the airline by raising doubts about its safety 
this type of manufactured alleged incident is typical of the 
safetyrelated scare tactics that the pilots union is using at 
this point eastern spokesman robin matell said 
matell said neville didnt feel he had been incapacitated after 
the auto accident after returning to miami the captain was checked 
out by easterns medical department and his private physician and 
was cleared to continue flying with a hairline fracture in his foot 
matell said 
this is not the type of thing you would even put a cast on 
matell said 
neville a resident of davie near fort lauderdale fla has an 
unlisted phone number and could not be reached for comment 
the pilots union called it to our attention last weekend and 
were looking into it said federal aviation administration 
spokesman jack barker in atlanta 
the medical report is being sent to the faa but has not yet 
arrived barker said 
besides the captain the cockpit crew reportedly included two 
recent graduates of easterns pilot training program 
