<TEXT>
the two broadest measures of the nations money 
supply rose in midjune but a narrower money measure fell the 
federal reserve board reported thursday 
the fed said the measure known as m2 rose 48 billion to a 
seasonally adjusted 30848 billion in the week ended june 12 from 
30800 billion the previous week 
an even broader measure m3 rose 75 billion to a seasonally 
adjusted 39708 billion from 39633 billion 
the narrowest measure of the money supply m1 slipped 66 
billion to a seasonally adjusted 7695 billion from 7761 billion 
m1 includes cash in circulation deposits in checking accounts 
and nonbank travelers checks m2 is m1 plus accounts like savings 
deposits and moneymarket mutual funds m3 is m2 plus lessliquid 
accounts such as certificates of deposit in minimum denominations 
of 100000 
in judging its monetary policy the fed has indicated it is 
monitoring the value of the dollar commodity prices and the 
difference between short and longterm interest rates it also has 
shifted its attention from m1 to the two broader money supply 
measures 
the fed in february reaffirmed a provisional target for 1989 of 3 
percent to 7 percent growth in m2 and 35 percent to 75 percent 
growth in m3 the fed has not set a target for m1 growth since early 
1987 
for the latest 13 weeks m2 averaged 30780 billion a 12 
percent seasonally adjusted annual rate of gain from the previous 13 
weeks m3 averaged 39570 billion up 34 percent while m1 fell 
45 percent to an average of 7788 billion 
in other reports 
the federal reserve bank of new york said bank borrowings from 
the federal reserve system at the discount window excluding 
extended credit averaged 546 million a day in the week ended 
wednesday up from 471 million the previous week 
the federal reserve bank of st louis reported that the monetary 
base the seasonally adjusted total of member bank reserves held at 
federal reserve banks and cash in bank vaults and in circulation 
was 2899 billion in the twoweek period ended wednesday up from 
2892 billion two weeks earlier 
