<TEXT>
canadian real estate giant olympia amp york 
developments ltd confirmed thursday it has made a bid for sears 
tower after the wall street journal reported the company was among 
four finalists vying for the worlds tallest building 
three other parties named by the newspaper as finalists for 
sears roebuck amp cos 110story building said they could not 
comment on the report 
the bids are said to range from 800 million to 1 billion which 
would be the highest price paid for an american building the wall 
street journal said citing individuals familiar with the 
process however the bids are probably below sears expectations 
a source told the newspaper 
we have submitted a bid said peter rosenthal a spokesman in 
new york for torontobased olympia amp york the largest private 
commercial real estate developer in north america he would not 
disclose the size of the bid and declined further comment 
the three other bidders named by the journal are chicago pension 
manager jmb realty corp with developer trammell crow co of dallas 
chicago developer lasalle partners inc with prudential insurance 
co of america and boston pension adviser aldrich eastman amp waltch 
inc 
lasalle partners vice president gretchen needham said her firm 
looks at every significant real estate opportunity in the 
country but would not confirm a bid for sears tower 
all the other companies named in the journal story referred 
telephone calls to senior executives or corporate spokespersons all 
of whom were said to be unavailable and did not return calls 
sears spokesman douglas fairweather said the journal did not get 
its information from sears 
were not commenting on the process of the sale its been 
going on for a while and we expect it will go on for a while he 
said when we have a deal well announce it 
even the lowest of the reported bids would top the highest price 
ever paid for a us building 660 million paid by walter 
shorenstein in 1985 for the bank of america building in san 
francisco 
but all the reported bids are below the 12 billion to 2 
billion that realestate experts expected the building would fetch 
when sears announced last october it would sell the downtown chicago 
landmark as part of a corporate restructuring 
the japanese government has discouraged japanese bids on sears 
tower fearing an antijapan backlash if they were to be successful 
in acquiring such a prominent piece of america said john oharenko 
a managing partner in the chicago office of cushman amp wakefield 
inc a new york real estate firm that has represented japanese 
buyers in other property deals 
the sears tower sale has been overshadowed lately by the 
companys plan to move its 6000employee merchandise group out of 
the tower to a location that the company expects to announce within 
a week 
illinois hopes to retain the retail arm of sears but several 
states including north carolina and texas also are in the running 
the merchandise group occupies most of the 50 lower floors of the 
tower the problem of finding tenants for those floors which are 
considered less desirable than the upper levels is one of the 
factors holding down the price tag for the building oharenko said 
